    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-01-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-01-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="496"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d496">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 83800/787.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-01-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 30, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>City quiet as a result of landing of marines and seamen. The <hi rend="italic"
                        >South Carolina</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Montana</hi> jointly have about
                    120 men ashore. Germans have 70 men ashore, and the British cruiser will land
                    men on her arrival to-day. French war vessel is on the way here from Mexico.
                    Presence of foreign war vessels and the landing of marines promises to
                    accomplish the peaceful choice of a President, which seemed to be impossible a
                    few days ago.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
